---
/**
 * The one v1 chaining demo (full chaining UI is out of scope, by decision):
 * a planetary reduction driving a torsion shaft. The legality table below is
 * computed at BUILD time by the same connectionLegal() the runtime planner
 * uses — the rejections shown are real engine verdicts, not prose.
 */
import { getCollection, getEntry } from "astro:content";
import ChainDemo from "../components/ChainDemo";
import { connectionLegal } from "../engines/units";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/url";

const gear = (await getEntry("compiled", "planetary-gearset"))!.data;
const shaft = (await getEntry("compiled", "torsion-shaft"))!.data;
const fourbar = (await getEntry("compiled", "fourbar-linkage"))!.data;
const column = (await getEntry("compiled", "euler-column"))!.data;

const boundKeys = Object.values(shaft.material_binding ?? {});
const materials = (await getCollection("materials"))
  .map((m) => m.data)
  .filter((m) => boundKeys.every((k) => m.properties.some((p) => p.key === k)));

type Compiled = typeof gear;
const port = (a: Compiled, s: string) => ({
  dim: a.variables[s]!.dim,
  quantity_kind: a.variables[s]!.quantity_kind,
});

const checks = [
  {
    from: "planetary T_out — torque, N·m",
    to: "shaft T — torque, N·m",
    res: connectionLegal(port(gear, "T_out"), port(shaft, "T")),
  },
  {
    from: "planetary ω_c — angular velocity, rad/s",
    to: "shaft ω — angular velocity, rad/s",
    res: connectionLegal(port(gear, "omega_c"), port(shaft, "omega")),
  },
  {
    from: "planetary ω_c — angular velocity, rad/s",
    to: "shaft T — torque, N·m",
    res: connectionLegal(port(gear, "omega_c"), port(shaft, "T")),
  },
  {
    from: "four-bar θ₄ — angle, dimensionless",
    to: "column K — ratio, dimensionless",
    res: connectionLegal(port(fourbar, "theta4"), port(column, "K")),
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Chaining demo"
  description="Two verified THINGs wired together: a planetary reduction driving a torsion shaft, with type-checked port bindings."
>
  <h1>Chaining: gearbox → output shaft</h1>
  <p>
    Every machine is THINGs wired together. Here a ring-fixed planetary reduction drives a solid
    shaft: the gearset's <em>torque delivered to the load</em> and <em>carrier speed</em> are bound
    to the shaft's <em>torque</em> and <em>speed</em> inputs. Turn the sun torque up, or trade
    tooth counts, and watch the consequences propagate into a different THING's stress, twist, and
    safety factor — then swap the shaft's material, which the gearbox upstream rightly never
    notices.
  </p>
  <p>
    Two numbers worth watching: the gearbox multiplies torque by 1 + N_r/N_s (3.5× at the default
    teeth) while dividing speed by the same factor — so the shaft's transmitted power
    <strong>P = Tω equals the input power T_s·ω_s exactly</strong> (ideal, lossless relations on
    both sides). Conservation laws survive the wiring; that is the point of verified chaining.
  </p>

  <div data-pagefind-ignore>
    <ChainDemo client:load gear={gear} shaft={shaft} materials={materials} />
  </div>

  <h2>Connections are type-checked</h2>
  <p>
    A binding is legal iff the SI dimension 7-vector <strong>and</strong> the quantity kind both
    match (invariant 2). Dimensions alone are not enough: an angle and a Poisson ratio are both
    dimensionless, and torque shares dimensions with energy. The verdicts below are produced by the
    same <code>connectionLegal()</code> the demo's planner runs — including the two rejections:
  </p>
  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table class="material-props">
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">From port</th><th scope="col">To port</th><th scope="col">Engine verdict</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          checks.map((c) => (
            <tr>
              <td>{c.from}</td>
              <td>{c.to}</td>
              <td>
                {c.res.ok ? (
                  <span class="chain-ok">legal</span>
                ) : (
                  <span class="chain-no">rejected — {c.res.reason}</span>
                )}
              </td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="citation">
    The planner also rejects any binding that would close a feedback loop — cyclic solving is out
    of scope in v1 (the relations are stored undirected, so a cyclic solver can be added later
    without rewriting THINGs; see the <a href={withBase("about/")}>about page</a> for scope).
    This page is the one chaining demo v1 ships; a full drag-and-wire UI is future work.
  </p>
</Base>
